    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="877"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d877">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.82/10–544</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Braden</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 4694</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-25">November 25,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: There is enclosed a copy of a letter from the
                    Navy Department<note n="27" xml:id="d877fn27">Not printed; it was dated October
                        5, 1944, and signed by Capt. O. S. Colclough.</note> stating that it is
                    desired that the aids to navigation established by the Coast Guard at Nuevitas
                    be transferred to the Cuban Government insofar as that Government is able to
                    assume the responsibility for their maintenance. It is requested that the
                    Embassy take up with the Cuban Government the question of the transfer of
                    responsibility in accordance with the Navy Department’s letter.<note n="28"
                        xml:id="d877fn28">There was no reply to this instruction in 1944. Although
                        maintenance of aids on fixed structures at Nuevitas was assumed by the Cuban
                        Navy in September, maintenance and servicing of all aids at Manzanillo and
                        the floating aids at Puerto de Nuevitas continued to be the responsibility
                        of the United States Coast Guard. (837.82/1–947)</note>
                </p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                    <signed>G. <hi rend="smallcaps">Howland Shaw</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
